#Download and decompress the following archive: https://ethz-ins.org/content/w10.assignment.zip This contains the bigwig files and peaks (bed) files for three TFs of the CREB family (all restricted to chr1; aligned against the hg38 genome)

options(timeout = 6000)
download.file("https://ethz-ins.org/content/w10.assignment.zip", "w10.assignment.zip")
unzip("w10.assignment.zip")
list.files()

#Use clustering and visualization to illustrate the relationship between the binding of the different proteins

Prepare the regions and the tracks

tracks <- list.files(pattern="bw$")
regions <- list.files(pattern="bed$")

##Identify peaks

peaks <- lapply(regions, rtracklayer::import.bed)
# we'll focus on the high-quality peaks
peaks <- lapply(peaks, FUN=function(x) x[x$score>800])
# we get the union of non-redundant regions
regions <- reduce(unlist(GRangesList(peaks)))

Plot

#2000 bases upstream and downstream of the regions
ml <- signal2Matrix(tracks, regions, extend=2000)
## Reading Creb1.bw
## Reading Creb3.bw
## Reading Creb3L1.bw
#vertically, the regions are sorted by intensity, with high intensity higher up, which is quite suboptimal to see patterns

# we could do extra normalization if needed
# nf <- getNormFactors(tracks, useSeqLevels="chr1")
# ml <- rescaleSignalMatrices(ml, scaleFactors=nf)

plotEnrichedHeatmaps(ml, colors=c("white", "purple"))

##Clustering ###Determine how many clusters we should be using by elbow method:

#trying from two to ten clusters
#give us proportion of variance explained (to establish how many clusters we should ideally use)
cls <- clusterSignalMatrices(ml, k = 2:10)
ggplot(cls$varExplained, aes(k, varExplained)) + geom_line()

#The elbow is at 3 clusters, but only 55% of variance explained
#Thus I will opt for 6 clusters, which explains ~76% of variance
#k (for clustering) = number of clusters
cl <- clusterSignalMatrices(ml, k = 6)
##   ~75% of the variance explained by clusters
#to get overview of clusters
table(cl)
## cl
##   1   2   3   4   5   6 
## 608  84 144 331 705 397

###Plot clustered heatmap

#create vector that associates each name of clusters (here digits) to a colour
mycolors <- c("1"="red", "2" = "blue", "3"="green", "4"= "black", "5" = "orange", "6" = "lightblue")
#pass this vector of colours to the heat map function
plotEnrichedHeatmaps(ml, colors=c("white", "purple"), row_split = cl, mean_color = mycolors)
## 'magick' package is suggested to install to give better rasterization.

#Use enrichment analysis (either GO or motif) on at least one of the clusters

##GO-term enrichment analysis to characterise the clusters

#split regions into the clusters
sp <- split(regions, cl)
names(sp)
## [1] "1" "2" "3" "4" "5" "6"
#for each cluster, I can get a GRanges of that cluster
#set your regions of interest and your background of regions
#provide regions in cluster sp[[]], and then as background the total list of regions
res <- rGREAT::submitGreatJob(sp[["6"]], bg = regions, species="hg38")
## Warning: From rGREAT 1.99.0, `bg` will not be supported any more because GREAT
## requires a special format for `gr` and `bg` if both are set, and it
## uses a completely different method for the enrichment analysis. Please
## see the documentation of `submitGreatJob()` for more explanations.
res2 <- rGREAT::getEnrichmentTables(res)
## The default enrichment tables contain no associated genes for the input
## regions.You can set `download_by = 'tsv'` to download the complete
## table,but note only the top 500 regions can be retreived. See the
## following link:
## 
## https://great-help.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/GREAT/pages/655401/Export#Export-GlobalExport
## 
## or you can try the local GREAT analysis with the function `great()`.
#organisation is hierarchical, with complexity/specificity increasing once you go further down

This suggests that the cluster that was being investigated contained genes that play a role in immunoregulatory tasks, which makes sense as we are looking at CREB, which is thought to have immunological function.
